1697,IssueComment,2021-03-04 14:45:25,rbouqueau,fork_close,"Hi David, many thanks for bootstrapping this.

@jeanlf @aureliendavid @cconcolato  Wouldn't it be an opportunity to consolidate the work started years ago with AFL?","{""url"": ""https://api.github.com/repos/gpac/gpac/issues/comments/790669286"", ""author_association"": ""CONTRIBUTOR""}"
FYI, we already run fuzzing on gpac in our CI platform, results here: https://tests.gpac.io/testres/fuzzing, but we don't yet have a public interface for submitting new fuzzing tests.
> FYI, we already run fuzzing on gpac in our CI platform, results here: https://tests.gpac.io/testres/fuzzing, but we don't yet have a public interface for submitting new fuzzing tests.

Ah that's great. I think OSS-Fuzz probably brings a fair amount of more features, amongst other things coverage, crash analysis and more. It also comes with a nice UI where you can browse all bugs and statistics. OSS-Fuzz also comes with continuous fuzzing and we can integrate it such that the fuzzers will be part of the CI as well, namely that the fuzzers is run for each new PR to the project.","{""url"": ""https://api.github.com/repos/gpac/gpac/issues/comments/792693301"", ""author_association"": ""NONE""}"
1697,IssueComment,2021-03-08 11:46:51,aureliendavid,fork_close,"This is interesting. I haven't had time to look into it in details yet.
If you have more info or documentation on what we would need to do on the gpac side to integrate with it, I'll take a look when I can.
1697,IssueComment,2021-03-08 12:17:28,DavidKorczynski,fork_close,"> This is interesting. I haven't had time to look into it in details yet.
> If you have more info or documentation on what we would need to do on the gpac side to integrate with it, I'll take a look when I can.

Essentially the only thing that is needed for getting this up and running is a set of emails that will receive notifications with bug reports (this is described in the first message of this PR). Then when this is merged in we can merge things on the OSS-Fuzz side and the fuzzer will start being run. ","{""url"": ""https://api.github.com/repos/gpac/gpac/issues/comments/792717885"", ""author_association"": ""NONE""}"

1697,IssueComment,2021-03-08 13:05:53,aureliendavid,fork_close,"I've only ever used afl+asan so I'll need to look into libfuzzer (that's what is used by oss-fuzz right?) to see how to add fuzzers and things like that.

Other than that I think it would be good to use this for gpac.
> Is storing fuzzers on the main repo mandatory? Because I think for us it would make more sense to store them in our tests repo (https://github.com/gpac/testsuite).
> Other than that I think it would be good to use this for gpac.

We can place the fuzzers anywhere. I can upload it to the testsuite repository or we can also start with keeping the fuzzers in the OSS-Fuzz repository - it's up to you! Let me know which you prefer and I will fix it up.
1697,IssueComment,2021-03-09 08:42:42,aureliendavid,fork_close,"> we can also start with keeping the fuzzers in the OSS-Fuzz repository
ok I think it would make sense to start like this (with the fuzzers in the oss-fuzz repo) while we get familiar with the tools
as for a maintainer email address, we can use: project.gpac@gmail.com

1709,IssueCommentSupplement,2022-02-24 10:41:44,Fatima212,unfork_merge,"I have successfully compiled MP4Box_android. But the problem is that I can only run the command line one time after the app was opened. If I run the command one more time, I will got this message in _/mnt/sdcard/stderrout.txt_ : ""Error - 2 input names specified, please check usage""","{""url"": ""https://api.github.com/repos/gpac/gpac/issues/comments/1049722685"", ""author_association"": ""NONE""}"
1709,IssueCommentSupplement,2022-03-01 16:46:40,aureliendavid,unfork_merge,"@Fatima212 you're right, it doesn't work properly on the second execution

this version was just a POC of a jni wrapper around mp4box, the problem is that, as a command line tool, the mp4box main() is not made to be called more than once (because there are a bunch of global variables that are not reset between calls)

I think the better solution would be to build a proper executable MP4Box command line for android, and maybe build a java gui that just calls it; but running and bundling binaries is a bit of a pain on android
what I did in the above commit is a hack in which the app restarts itself after each execution of mp4box, I also added a field to display the log of the previous execution:
it's a bit clunky but it kinda works ","{""url"": ""https://api.github.com/repos/gpac/gpac/issues/comments/1055640971"", ""author_association"": ""CONTRIBUTOR""}"

After reading some .c files, I figure out this error occurs because `inName` variable  is not reset. https://github.com/gpac/gpac/blob/7b64a5c3b51abd225d6e869e8e8a8057d18a07cb/applications/mp4box/main.c#L245
I have set `inName = NULL` in first line of `mp4boxMain` function so that `inName ` is reset every time mp4boxMain is called.
Rebuilding mp4box libs, my mp4box_android application can run without restart.
1709,IssueCommentSupplement,2022-03-12 12:18:57,aureliendavid,unfork_merge,"yes in this particular it was inName that was not reset and caused the ""2 input files"" error

but in the general case there might be other stuff that are not reinitialized between runs, so I figured reloading the whole thing safer ","{""url"": ""https://api.github.com/repos/gpac/gpac/issues/comments/1065873632"", ""author_association"": ""CONTRIBUTOR""}"

1915,IssueComment,2021-10-04 16:30:54,cconcolato,unfork_merge,"For the record, with this PR, MP4Box manipulates HDR data as follows:
- ""-diso"" dumps the values from the boxes as integers (see SmDm_box_dump and mdcv_box_dump)
- ""-dnal"" dumps (this PR) values as floats (dividing  by the corresponding MPEG vs. AOM max value based on the stream type)
- ""-hdr"" (https://github.com/gpac/gpac/commit/b8e7d96a53a106606fed9af71f9093636f44b08f) takes integers in the MPEG space to generate MPEG boxes (not VP9 boxes).
